This entry is based on one source in the HRAF archive dealing ì with the government of Ethiopia and its political divisions, and ì on three smaller sources. The first contains a collection of ì folktales from Amhara peasants and nobles collected in 1953-54. ì The second is a brief description of medical problems and ì diseases in Ethiopia during 1944-45. This treatment tends toward ì generality and is less temporally specific than one would expect. ì The third is an essay on the physical and racial characteristics ì of the Amhara. Together, these sources give an introduction to ì some important cultural artifacts and assess medical problems ì during one time period.

Focus Note: The Yanoama, Waica, Pakidai, Suara, Shiriana, and Sanema entries ì share a single problem: the designation of the language spoken by ì each. PSF-A uses Yanoama (Yanoamo) as an ethnolinguistic ì classification to designate the following small ethnic groups ì located in southern Venezuela and Brazil:Sanema, Nabudub, ì Pubmatari, Tadaubub, Waica, Shiriana, Karime, Samatari, Suara, ì and Pakidai. These occupy contiguous areas and their languages ì are closely related (PSF-A:486). The Ethnologue has entries for ì the following languages in Venezuela: Sanema, Ninam, and Yanoamo. ì The Brazil enetry adds Yanoami (Waica). Ethnographic data in the ì HRAF archive is less than specific on matters of geographical ì location and linguistic classification in this case. This ì information should, therefore, be used with caution. Note ì especially that PSF-A assumes an overarching linguistic ì relationship to exist between these groups whereas the Ethnologue ì has pin-pointed specific languages other than Yanoamo. When such ì languages have been cited in the Ethnologue, these have been ì noted in the appropriate concordance entry. When no such citation ì exists, the language has been listed as Yanoamo in agreement with ì the information contained in PSF-A.
Special reference is made to the Guajajara subgroup.

Focus Note: This entry is based largely upon the sources in the HRAF archive ì authored by Wilbert (7,16,22,24, and 32) that contain data ì general information on the Warao gathered over a fifteen to twenty one year ì period. Partial use of HRAF 2,4, and 27 is also advised.
The focus of this entry is on the Hoanarao people and various sub-tribes of the ì Orinoco Delta including the Mariusa, Winikina, and Arawabisi.
Special reference is made to the Winikina Warao.

The author of HRAF 26 (p. 16) lists the five most important Warao villages on the ì Winikina River but gives no indication that his study is confined ì to any one of these. HRAF 29 (p. 28) mentions the central Orinoco ì Delta, but notes no specific village as a single focus. HRAF 9 ì (p. 93) mentions that the Winikina-Warao of the central to ì southern Orinoco Delta as the subject of investigation.
